  abstract    = {Heavy storms during the March 1980 herring spawning period resulted in substantial deposition of uprooted vegetation and spawn in the vicinity of French Creek. Total volume of washed up material, consisting of eggs, vegetation and debris was estimated at 497 cu m, of which 68% by weight was herring spawn. The total estimated egg number was 5.76 x 10 to the 10th power, which was approximately 25% of the total egg deposition in the immediate vicinity of French Creek. Based on a conversion factor of 10 to the eighth power eggs per ton of fish, the egg loss represents the spawning capacity of about 576 tons of fish, which is not a substantial quantity when compared with the established stock in the Strait of Georgia. However, it is possible the deleterious effects of storms on spawn deposition may be widespread, but only noted in specific locations when phenomenal quantities are washed ashore.},
