  type        = {Canadian Technical Report of Fisheries and Aquatic Sciences},
  number      = {1372},
  url         = {http://cat.fsl-bsf.scitech.gc.ca/record=b1319605~S1},
  abstract    = {The herring spawn-on-kelp fishery in British Columbia is an important commedcal fishery which can produce a high quality product using a small amount of herring. Investigations of spawn-on-kelp operations on the north coast and the Queen Charlotte Islands were carried out in 1982 and 1983. Herring mortalities were low during the capture, towing, and transfer of herring to impoundments; subsequent high mortalities appear to be the result of excessively high loading densities. Water quality in the
impoundments remained high in spite of heavy egg coverage along the inside of the web. Depending on fish maturity and harvest methods, the quota for one licence (7.26 t of product) was estimated to require 28.6 to 63.5 t of hering. This does not consider the quantity of herring lost because of mortality before or after the fishery operations.
Alternative harvest methods such as "open ponds" have several advantages over the more traditional methods but are not suitable for all areas. An important factor limiting the spawn-an-kelp fishery is the availability of high quality kelp.},
