  abstract    = {The herring roe on seaweed fishery in Georgia Strait suffers from the absence of the giant kelp Macrocystis integrifolia in that location. Studies have revealed that the alga can be harvested, transported and held in a viable form for four weeks prior to use in propagation ponds. Salt preservation of the plant can be effected but rapid biodeterioration results from reimmersion of the preserved tissue in seawater, thus pre-season collection and storage by chemical preservation is impossible. The herring roe on seaweed assimilates salt rapidly when treated with saturated brine, a medium in which the quality can best be maintained at the lowest possible storage temperature.},
